Data Wrangling

Ajay Koli

3 Dec, 2020 | updated on 07 Dec 2020

Hello, you all are welcomed to topic number 2 which is data wrangling. In this session you will learn:

  • how to import/export data
  • to perform data manipulation for rows
  • to perform data manipulation for columns
  • to calculate summary statistics for the variables

Data wrangling is focused upon the data exploration and data manipulation (Jesse Mostipak). As per Hadley & Garrett together tidy and transforming are called wrangling. Tidy data means that data should be stored in a consistent format in which each row represents an unique observation and each column represents an unique variable. Data transformation means narrowing in on observations of interest creating new variables that are functions of existing variables and calculating a set of summary statistics.

1 Data - Palmer Penguins

We will be using Palmer Penguins data. It is a data about 344 penguins (sample/observations) and 8 variables (columns):

  • species : a factor denoting penguin species (Adlie, Chinstrap and Gentoo)
  • island : a factor denoting island in Palmer Archipelago, Antarctica (Biscoe, Dream or Torgersen)
  • bill_length_mm : a number denoting bill length (millimeters)
  • bill_depth_mm : a number denoting bill depth (millimeters)
  • flipper_length_mm : an integer denoting flipper length (millimeters)
  • body_mass_g : an integer denoting body mass (grams)
  • sex : a factor denoting penguin sex (female, male)
  • year : an integer denoting the study year (2007, 2008, or 2009)

Types of the variables:

  • int stands for integers.
  • dbl stands for doubles, or real numbers.
  • chr stands for character vectors, or strings.
  • dttm stands for date-times (a date + a time).
  • lgl stands for logical, vectors that contain only TRUE or FALSE.
  • fct stands for factors, which R uses to represent categorical variables with fixed possible values.
  • date stands for dates.

1.1 Import data

library(readr)
penguins <- read_csv("data/penguins.csv",
  col_types = cols(
    species = col_factor(),
    island = col_factor(),
    bill_length_mm = col_double(),
    bill_depth_mm = col_double(),
    flipper_length_mm = col_integer(),
    body_mass_g = col_integer(),
    sex = col_factor(),
    year = col_integer()
  )
)
library(dplyr)

2 Data manipulation using dplyr package

# use tidyverse package
library(tidyverse)

# or just use dplyr
# library(dplyr)

tidyverse is a set of these packages:

  • ggplot2, for data visualisation.

  • dplyr, for data manipulation.

  • tidyr, for data tidying.

  • readr, for data import.

  • purrr, for functional programming.

  • tibble, for tibbles, a modern re-imagining of data frames.

  • stringr, for strings.

  • forcats, for factors.

Five key functions from dplyr package:

  1. Pick observations by their values using function filter().

  2. Reorder the rows using function arrange().

  3. Pick variables by their names using function select().

  4. Create new variables with functions of existing variables using function mutate().

  5. Collapse many values down to a single summary using function summarise().

as this site explains these functions can be categories based upon:

  • Rows:

    • filter() chooses rows based on column values.
    • slice() chooses rows based on location.
    • arrange() changes the order of the rows.

  • Columns:

    • select() changes whether or not a column is included.
    • rename() changes the name of columns.
    • mutate() changes the values of columns and creates new columns.
    • relocate() changes the order of the columns.

  • Groups of rows:

    • summarise() collapses a group into a single row.

You may have noticed that the syntax and function of all these verbs are very similar:

  • The first argument is a data frame.

  • The subsequent arguments describe what to do with the data frame. You can refer to columns in the data frame directly without using $.

  • The result is a new data frame

2.1 Pipes

%>% this is called pipe. It comes from the r package magrittr.

  • allow you to express a sequence of multiple operations

[I]t focuses on verbs, not nouns. by Hadley

  • you dont assign anything within the pipes

  • Remember to add the pipe %>% at the end of each line involved in the piped operation

7 Based upon group of rows

penguins %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  group_by(island) %>%
  summarise(mean(bill_length_mm))
# A tibble: 3 x 2
  island    `mean(bill_length_mm)`
  <fct>                      <dbl>
1 Torgersen                   39.0
2 Biscoe                      45.2
3 Dream                       44.2
